Main Scanning Logic
basic_tcp_scan

This function scans a selected port range.

It works by:

Creating a socket.
Trying to connect to each port.
If connection succeeds, the port is open.
If connection fails, the port is closed or filtered.

Why it is useful:

Simple
Beginner friendly
Helps understand how port scanning works internally
common_ports_scan

This scans only popular ports like:

21, 22, 80, 443, 3306, 8080

Why useful:

Faster than full scan
Good for quick recon
Beginner friendly
run_command

This function runs custom Nmap commands.

Example:

nmap -sV 192.168.1.1

Why useful:

Lets advanced users use real Nmap options
Supports service scan, OS detection, aggressive scan, UDP scan, etc.
Makes the GUI flexible

It only allows commands starting with:

nmap

This makes it safer than allowing any system command.

GUI Logic
PortScannerApp

This class creates the full desktop app.

It contains:

IP input box
Start port box
End port box
Scan type dropdown
Custom command field
Start scan button
Result popup window
get_target

Checks whether the user entered an IP or hostname.

get_ports

If no ports are entered, it uses default:

1-1024

Why useful:

Beginners can scan without knowing port ranges
Prevents empty input errors
show_result_popup

Shows scan result in a separate window.

Why useful:

Main window stays clean
Results are easy to read
Looks more professional
start_scan

This decides which scan type to run.

Example:

Basic TCP Scan → Python socket scan
Common Ports Scan → predefined common ports
Nmap scans → runs Nmap command
Custom Nmap Command → user-defined Nmap command
